snippet.textDisplay:
Pasteurized milk is the real issue here. Raw milk contains lactase in order to deliver the means to digest it and assimilate it. Raw milk is easier on digestion simply it hasn't been sterilized of bacteria and enzymes required to break it down in the body.
Also, small intestinal bacterial overgrowths or SIBO for short is a condition in which the small intestine developes inappropriate and improper amounts of bacteria (which should be fairly sterile) this bacterial overgrowth leads to chronic inflammation of the gut and small holes develop along the mucosal lining of the intestine. Lactase enzymes which should be present in this part of the intestine slip through into the blood stream where the immune system sees it as a foreign invader and develops an immune response. This is likely why people are lactose intolerant. Many things contribute to SIBO, such as not enough stomach acid (your first line of defense), pollutants and heavy metals in your environment, too much raw vegetables and leafy greens, nuts, seeds and beans, all can irritate the digestive system and alkalize our stomachs which should be somewhere between 1 to 3 on a ph scale.. that's enough to melt marble. Milk isnt controversial, our treatment and abuse of it along with a misaligned immune system from our modern plaque of a society is.

snippet.textDisplay: the whole part about villinising farms and making dairy farming look like its is cruel..... it is not cruel. Take it from someone who has worked on a dairy farm and many different types of farming like grain beef and dairy I have and farming is nothing like what people think it is about. Farmers love the animals that they produce ill give an example it's like buying and investing into a house and then just completely trashing the whole house and losing money on it when you sell it that is what it would be like if farmers did not treat there animals good. To the farmers the animal is there life and there investment they are not going to ruin that investment. Iunderstand that there is animal cruelty in this world and that cruelty to animals happen but farms that are producing food for our world and our greater population do not go out of there way to be cruel to there animals. I have worked on many farms and seen first hand what happens on dairy farms.... yes we take the calves but only so that the mother can go back into milk production, on some farms the mothers milk is given to the calves by bottles and on some farms they use milk replacer it is not inhumane to do this stuff. The mother does bawle for about a day or so and then she forgets she even had a calve...... they dont have the same kind of feelings that humans have they dont think the same way. Yes they have feelings but they dont have the knowledge to feel the same way a human feels so when there calf is taken away they may want it for a little bit but then with a couple of hours or a so they forget they even had it. Sometimes a first time calver will even abandon the calf because it's never had a calf before and it doesn't understand what to do with the calf. So the farmer takes the calf because they can provide better care for the calf than most cows can. The whole thing  with cows being artificially inseminated is not inhumane either a cow naturally goes into heat regularly and needs and wants to become pregnant so the farmers are giving her what the cow naturally needs. They are not forcibly impregnating them the cow wants to be pregnant and how you know that is by seeing her riding other cows. I really dont like how this video is making farms look bad they are not bad and if you want to know what actually happens then look up educational videos on farms because you will learn alot more about what happens on farms than being told just that they are bad. FARMERS FEED CITIES PEOPLE.

snippet.textDisplay: Many of the concerns over milk's health effects are related to the use of rBGH (recombinant bovine growth hormone) in many industrialized countries like the US to boost milk production in dairy cows. Substances like rBGH pass into the milk itself, and can act as a molecular trigger that can randomly stimulate cellular growth - meaning it can just as easily trigger growth of cancer cells as it does other tissues in the human body. It is suspected by some that steady milk consumption of rBGH-laced milk is responsible for not only a number of different cancers, but for premature/excessive breast development in prepubescent and pubescent girls. This is one of the reasons why the subject of milk's health effects is a complicated issue, because a crucial component of the matter relates to how that milk is produced and whether a farm utilizes growth hormones to increase their yields.

snippet.textDisplay:
I find this video to be biased. While it states correctly that two thirds of the world population are lactose intolerant, it goes on to say repeatedly in the video that "[milk] it's not harmful for the majority of the population", which is an obvious contradiction and, as correctly pointed out in their own map, a racially biased one, since the only part of the world population that can mostly digest lactose in adulthood is white - the video even goes on to show an adult black person drinking milk, which is most likely wrong for them. Milk is currently part of official food recommendations in western countries, and it should be removed for this reason alone.


The video goes on to add more factual mistakes. It states that the evidence against milk is controversial by putting the pro and con studies on the same level, or many con studies on balance with "a few" inconclusive ones, and it fails to recognise that the studies in favour of milk often suffer a conflict of interest or are problematic in method (meta), as they are often funded by the dairy industry itself, or compare "healthy" effects of animal products against inherently unhealthy alternatives. This is particularly true for the studies around brittle bones, cancer and IGF factor. And while it does say correctly that milk is unnecessary, it still goes on to compare oat, rice, almond and soy milk unfavorably, failing to mention that none of them suffer any of the "controversies" that affect cow milk and animal milk in general, which in and on itself should be ground for preferring vegetable milks and for including any of them instead of animal milk in any official recommendation. It also downplays the risk of weight gain caused by milk consumption, which is indeed a very serious risk, as weight alone is a strong predictor of both lifespan and healthspan. This effect is very important, as the difference in BMI between vegan and vegetarian on average is a known fact, and it strongly favors veganism (no milk, no eggs).

To my surprise the video even presents milk as a food with "all essential macronutrients" , which is a common mistake, as milk contains no fiber, a neglected yet very much essential nutrient, and while you can certainly say that milk contains "many micronutrients", if you compare those many to the total of the ones necessary to a healthy diet, you might easily get the opposite impression: that it's not actually that many, and also that plenty of these micronutrients are present in amounts so large as to be potentially unhealthy (and calcium would be a prime example of this, since in those amounts it's meant to feed calves to grow about as big as 5 to 10 human adults in a few short months).


As always I commend the effort, but the result this time is underwhelming.
snippet.textOriginal:
I find this video to be biased. While it states correctly that two thirds of the world population are lactose intolerant, it goes on to say repeatedly in the video that "[milk] it's not harmful for the majority of the population", which is an obvious contradiction and, as correctly pointed out in their own map, a racially biased one, since the only part of the world population that can mostly digest lactose in adulthood is white - the video even goes on to show an adult black person drinking milk, which is most likely wrong for them. Milk is currently part of official food recommendations in western countries, and it should be removed for this reason alone.


The video goes on to add more factual mistakes. It states that the evidence against milk is controversial by putting the pro and con studies on the same level, or many con studies on balance with "a few" inconclusive ones, and it fails to recognise that the studies in favour of milk often suffer a conflict of interest or are problematic in method (meta), as they are often funded by the dairy industry itself, or compare "healthy" effects of animal products against inherently unhealthy alternatives. This is particularly true for the studies around brittle bones, cancer and IGF factor. And while it does say correctly that milk is unnecessary, it still goes on to compare oat, rice, almond and soy milk unfavorably, failing to mention that none of them suffer any of the "controversies" that affect cow milk and animal milk in general, which in and on itself should be ground for preferring vegetable milks and for including any of them instead of animal milk in any official recommendation. It also downplays the risk of weight gain caused by milk consumption, which is indeed a very serious risk, as weight alone is a strong predictor of both lifespan and healthspan. This effect is very important, as the difference in BMI between vegan and vegetarian on average is a known fact, and it strongly favors veganism (no milk, no eggs).
 
To my surprise the video even presents milk as a food with "all essential macronutrients" , which is a common mistake, as milk contains no fiber, a neglected yet very much essential nutrient, and while you can certainly say that milk contains "many micronutrients", if you compare those many to the total of the ones necessary to a healthy diet, you might easily get the opposite impression: that it's not actually that many, and also that plenty of these micronutrients are present in amounts so large as to be potentially unhealthy (and calcium would be a prime example of this, since in those amounts it's meant to feed calves to grow about as big as 5 to 10 human adults in a few short months).


As always I commend the effort, but the result this time is underwhelming.

snippet.textDisplay:
The problem with Milk, at least in western countries and especially the US is...wait for it...capitalism! Got a whole lot of grazing and dairy ability in the US. So, rather than have it just be another foodstuff that people can eat if they want to, it has to be advertised and pushed in order to maintain the 'market' which leads to all sorts of distorted marketing and advertising and that's before you even get to the regulatory capture aspect of it all. I may be a bit older, but until the end of the 90's it was basically an axiom that milk was always healthy. There was literally no downside to its consumption, even from a basic "you really shouldn't overdo it with this, like any other food." Milk was considered good, period. Consuming it was considered good, period.



See how that can cause potential problems?



This is true for so many different quirks of our food production and consumption here, but it is what it is. I don't think milk is inherently anything other than a nutrient dense food we can squeeze from livestock, but once you make a market...the bullshit starts, so to speak.
